	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I'm level 18 now and would like to try to put some balance on the weight/AC/armor questions.<BR>
<BR>
At lower levels (say up to 12), max out your leather armor. The weight gain/AC loss is nothing compared to the AC value of the armor. I tested this with all of my armor, and there was no peice of leather armor that I dropped that gave me an ac bonus over wearing teh armor, until I got to about level 15, where it was about even.<BR>
<BR>
So young monks wear that armor! I never noticed a penalty to attacks, contrary to what others have claimed. However, always be willing to drop some platinum on lighter armor when the opportunity arises - having low armor weight and high AC is the best combination (duh).<BR>
<BR>
Also, learn throwing shuriken early in life - I gpot a late start. Shuriken are great for &quot;pulling&quot; monsters; you can often get back to your party or zone edge without taking a single hit by using a shuriken to get their attention. When you need to step out of a battle, you can still assist by hurling them back into the fray.<BR>
<BR>
Go for money rich targets, and spend that loot on bandages. Become a master bandager - at skill 40, you should be healing 8 or 9 points per attempt, which can save your butt when poisoned, and will make you a lot of friends. I started late, and regret it constantly.<BR>
<BR>
By level 9 get those mesh or netted gloves, and hunt wisps. The are easy to find, fairly safe, and carry a ton of loot.<BR>
<BR>
To rapidly get through levels 12 to 14, hunt the long border between north and west Karana - lots of beetles, wolves and cats, no poisons, and only griffins to watch out for. Pull to the border, and run if you get to 1 bubble of health. Losing a kill is nothing compared to losing a life.<BR>
<BR>
For magic items, I highly recommend increasing your magic resistance. Magic  will stomp you flat as a warrior type, but wolf's eye agate jewelry can save your butt. also, get a snakeskin mask from Paw.<BR>
<BR>
Nothing you do to your stats seems to matter a whole lot. Don't get uptight about it. Ignore wisdom, though. There are lots of magic items to increase stats, anyways.<BR>
<BR>
Get Large sewing kits to carry things in, instead of backpacks. saves about 3 pounds in weight each, but dont hit combine!<BR>
<BR>
Tailoring is a waste - by the time you get good enough to make higher qualities of armor, you will be able to acquire mesh, netted, snakeskin and other stuff, much better and much cheaper. No one will buy studded leather from you, unless it is the enchanted kind from orcs.<BR>
<BR>
Never hunt befallen until level 15 or better. People constantly drag level 15+ monsters up from the second level, and out of 12 trips, only one had me leaving with more experience than when I entered.<BR>
<BR>
Put 1 skill point into all combat abilities, and let them go up by themselves. save them for feign death, and instill doubt, and sneak (great for corpse retreival!). Put points into throwing, though.<BR>
<BR>
By level 15, you shout start worrying about weight more. I was always around 30 until then, now I stay below 15 with no loot. Go sell if you get above 40, and try to pick monsters which carry light loot, like gems, spider silk, poison sacs, etc. Use the money for magic items, and bandages.<BR>
<BR>
I'm really serious about the bandages - you can heal 20 points at skill 100. <BR>
<BR>
Good hunting!
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
